/* CISM :: content/quiz3.js — CISM Domain 3 question bank (100 items). */
window.CISM = window.CISM || {}; CISM.questions = CISM.questions || [];
CISM.questions.push.apply(CISM.questions, [
{"id":"D3-001","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"easy","q":"An information security manager is building the information security program. Which document should be developed FIRST to guide the program's overall direction?","options":["An information security strategy","Detailed technical standards","A security awareness training deck","An incident response runbook"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>An information security strategy</strong> — the strategy translates business objectives and risk appetite into program direction, and every subsequent standard, control, and initiative is derived from it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Detailed technical standards</b>: standards implement strategic direction; writing them first risks controls that do not align with business priorities.</span><span class='qd'><b>A security awareness training deck</b>: training content should reflect strategic priorities and policies that do not yet exist at this stage.</span><span class='qd'><b>An incident response runbook</b>: response procedures are operational detail that should follow, not precede, the overall program strategy.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-002","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"easy","q":"The PRIMARY purpose of an information security program charter is to:","options":["Formally establish the program's authority, scope, and sponsorship","List every technical control to be deployed","Document the results of the most recent risk assessment","Define the disaster recovery time objectives"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Formally establish the program's authority, scope, and sponsorship</strong> — the charter is a governance document that grants the security manager the mandate, resources, and executive backing needed to run the program.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>List every technical control to be deployed</b>: control-level detail belongs in standards and design documents, not the charter.</span><span class='qd'><b>Document the results of the most recent risk assessment</b>: risk assessment results inform the program but are a separate deliverable.</span><span class='qd'><b>Define the disaster recovery time objectives</b>: RTOs belong to business continuity planning, a downstream activity supported by the program.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-003","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"easy","q":"An organization's information security program road map spans three years. Which factor is MOST important when sequencing initiatives on the road map?","options":["Dependencies between initiatives and their relative risk reduction","Vendor marketing timelines for new products","The personal preference of the security manager","Alphabetical order of initiative names"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Dependencies between initiatives and their relative risk reduction</strong> — sequencing should ensure prerequisite capabilities are built first and that the highest risk-reduction, most resource-feasible initiatives are prioritized.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor marketing timelines for new products</b>: road maps should be driven by organizational risk and need, not vendor sales cycles.</span><span class='qd'><b>The personal preference of the security manager</b>: sequencing must be objective and risk-based, not subjective.</span><span class='qd'><b>Alphabetical order of initiative names</b>: an arbitrary ordering ignores dependencies and business risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-004","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"hard","q":"When developing the information security program road map, the security manager discovers that two planned initiatives compete for the same limited budget. What should the manager do FIRST?","options":["Prioritize based on risk reduction and alignment with business objectives","Cancel both initiatives to avoid conflict","Fund whichever initiative was proposed first","Split the budget evenly regardless of risk impact"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Prioritize based on risk reduction and alignment with business objectives</strong> — limited resources should be allocated to the initiative that most reduces risk and best supports strategic goals, using a defensible, risk-based rationale.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cancel both initiatives to avoid conflict</b>: abandoning needed initiatives ignores the underlying risk they address.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fund whichever initiative was proposed first</b>: submission order has no bearing on risk or business value.</span><span class='qd'><b>Split the budget evenly regardless of risk impact</b>: even splitting may underfund the higher-risk initiative and waste resources on the lower-priority one.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-005","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"easy","q":"Which control framework is MOST widely used as an international standard for establishing, implementing, and maintaining an information security management system (ISMS)?","options":["ISO/IEC 27001","ITIL","PMBOK","TOGAF"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>ISO/IEC 27001</strong> — it is the internationally recognized standard specifying requirements for establishing, implementing, maintaining, and continually improving an ISMS.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ITIL</b>: a framework for IT service management, not an ISMS certification standard.</span><span class='qd'><b>PMBOK</b>: a project management body of knowledge, unrelated to information security management systems.</span><span class='qd'><b>TOGAF</b>: an enterprise architecture framework, not a security management standard.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-006","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"easy","q":"An organization wants a control catalog with prioritized, prescriptive safeguards commonly used as a baseline for hardening systems. Which resource is MOST appropriate?","options":["CIS Critical Security Controls","COBIT","Balanced Scorecard","ISO 9001"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>CIS Critical Security Controls</strong> — the CIS Controls provide a prioritized, prescriptive set of safeguards specifically designed as actionable hardening and defense baselines.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>COBIT</b>: a governance and management framework for enterprise IT, broader and less prescriptive than a technical control catalog.</span><span class='qd'><b>Balanced Scorecard</b>: a performance-management tool for strategic measurement, not a security control catalog.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 9001</b>: a quality management standard, not focused on technical security safeguards.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-007","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"hard","q":"NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF) functions include Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, and Govern. In which function would asset inventory and risk assessment activities PRIMARILY reside?","options":["Identify","Protect","Respond","Recover"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Identify</strong> — this function covers understanding the organizational context, including asset inventories, business environment, and risk assessment, which underpin all other functions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Protect</b>: focuses on safeguards to limit or contain the impact of a potential event, which follows identification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Respond</b>: covers activities taken during and after a detected incident, not baseline asset and risk understanding.</span><span class='qd'><b>Recover</b>: addresses restoring capabilities after an incident, unrelated to initial asset inventory.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-008","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"hard","q":"An enterprise uses COBIT to govern IT while also implementing ISO/IEC 27001 for its ISMS. What is the MOST accurate description of how these frameworks should be used together?","options":["COBIT provides governance and management objectives while ISO 27001 provides ISMS implementation requirements, and the two can be mapped for a cohesive program","COBIT replaces the need for ISO 27001 entirely","ISO 27001 should be discarded because COBIT already certifies security","The two frameworks cannot be used in the same organization"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>COBIT provides governance and management objectives while ISO 27001 provides ISMS implementation requirements, and the two can be mapped for a cohesive program</strong> — COBIT addresses broader IT governance and control objectives, and organizations commonly cross-map it with ISO 27001's ISMS controls to avoid duplication and strengthen assurance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>COBIT replaces the need for ISO 27001 entirely</b>: COBIT is a governance framework, not a certifiable ISMS standard; it does not replace ISO 27001.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 27001 should be discarded because COBIT already certifies security</b>: COBIT is not a certification scheme for an ISMS.</span><span class='qd'><b>The two frameworks cannot be used in the same organization</b>: many organizations successfully integrate both frameworks through control mapping.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-009","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"easy","q":"In the policy hierarchy, which document establishes mandatory, specific technical requirements that support a policy?","options":["Standard","Guideline","Policy","Procedure"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Standard</strong> — standards are mandatory, specific requirements (e.g., minimum password length) that operationalize the intent stated in a higher-level policy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Guideline</b>: guidelines are recommended, not mandatory, practices.</span><span class='qd'><b>Policy</b>: policies state high-level intent and management direction, not specific technical values.</span><span class='qd'><b>Procedure</b>: procedures describe step-by-step tasks to implement standards, not the requirement itself.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-010","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"easy","q":"A document that provides step-by-step instructions for performing a specific security task, such as configuring a firewall rule, is BEST classified as a:","options":["Policy","Standard","Procedure","Guideline"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Procedure</strong> — procedures are detailed, sequential instructions for carrying out a task in a consistent and repeatable manner.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Policy</b>: states high-level management intent, not step-by-step instructions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Standard</b>: defines mandatory requirements but not the detailed how-to steps.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guideline</b>: offers optional, discretionary advice rather than mandatory step-by-step direction.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-011","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"easy","q":"A business unit wants to deviate from a mandatory encryption standard due to a legacy application constraint. What is the MOST appropriate course of action?","options":["Submit a formal exception request through the defined risk-acceptance process","Ignore the standard since the application is legacy","Rewrite the standard to accommodate the one application","Allow the deviation informally without documentation"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Submit a formal exception request through the defined risk-acceptance process</strong> — documented exceptions ensure the risk is evaluated, accepted by an appropriate authority, and tracked for remediation or compensating controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore the standard since the application is legacy</b>: unmanaged noncompliance hides risk from governance oversight.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rewrite the standard to accommodate the one application</b>: weakening an enterprise standard for a single exception undermines its purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>Allow the deviation informally without documentation</b>: informal, undocumented exceptions bypass accountability and audit trails.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-012","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"hard","q":"Which statement BEST describes the relationship between policies and guidelines?","options":["Policies state mandatory intent while guidelines offer recommended, discretionary practices","Guidelines are mandatory while policies are optional","They are interchangeable terms for the same document type","Guidelines override policies when in conflict"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Policies state mandatory intent while guidelines offer recommended, discretionary practices</strong> — policies set enforceable direction from management, whereas guidelines suggest good practices that may be adapted to context.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Guidelines are mandatory while policies are optional</b>: this reverses the actual hierarchy of enforceability.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are interchangeable terms for the same document type</b>: each serves a distinct governance purpose and level of authority.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guidelines override policies when in conflict</b>: policies carry higher authority; guidelines never override them.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-013","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"easy","q":"Which enterprise architecture approach layers multiple, independent security controls so that if one control fails, others continue to protect the asset?","options":["Defense-in-depth","Zero trust","Single sign-on","Data minimization"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Defense-in-depth</strong> — this approach deliberately layers diverse, overlapping controls (network, host, application, physical) so a single point of failure does not fully expose an asset.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Zero trust</b>: a philosophy of never implicitly trusting any entity and continuously verifying, which is complementary but conceptually distinct from layering.</span><span class='qd'><b>Single sign-on</b>: an authentication convenience mechanism, not a layered-defense architecture.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data minimization</b>: a privacy principle limiting data collection, not a control-layering architecture.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-014","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"easy","q":"An organization adopting a zero trust architecture would MOST likely implement which principle?","options":["Continuous verification of identity and device posture for every access request regardless of network location","Implicit trust for all traffic originating inside the corporate network perimeter","A single perimeter firewall as the sole access control","Granting broad access by default and restricting only known-bad actors"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Continuous verification of identity and device posture for every access request regardless of network location</strong> — zero trust assumes no implicit trust and requires ongoing verification of identity, device health, and context before granting access.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Implicit trust for all traffic originating inside the corporate network perimeter</b>: this is the traditional perimeter-based model zero trust explicitly rejects.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single perimeter firewall as the sole access control</b>: zero trust moves away from reliance on a single perimeter control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Granting broad access by default and restricting only known-bad actors</b>: this default-allow posture contradicts zero trust's default-deny, least-privilege approach.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-015","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"hard","q":"A security architect is designing network segmentation for a manufacturing environment with both IT and operational technology (OT) systems. Which design objective should be given the HIGHEST priority?","options":["Maximizing bandwidth between IT and OT networks","Using identical security controls for IT and OT to simplify management","Isolating OT systems to limit lateral movement from a compromised IT segment","Allowing unrestricted remote access to OT devices for convenience"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Isolating OT systems to limit lateral movement from a compromised IT segment</strong> — OT environments often run legacy, safety-critical systems that cannot tolerate typical IT patching or downtime, so segmentation is the primary control to contain a breach originating in IT.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Maximizing bandwidth between IT and OT networks</b>: high connectivity increases attack surface and contradicts the isolation goal.</span><span class='qd'><b>Using identical security controls for IT and OT to simplify management</b>: OT systems often cannot support the same controls (e.g., agents, frequent patching) as IT and require tailored approaches.</span><span class='qd'><b>Allowing unrestricted remote access to OT devices for convenience</b>: unrestricted remote access to safety-critical OT systems creates severe risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-016","domain":3,"obj":"3A5","diff":"hard","q":"When classifying organizational assets, which factor is MOST important in determining the classification level of a data set?","options":["The file format in which the data is stored","The age of the data set","The impact to the organization if the data's confidentiality, integrity, or availability is compromised","The department that originally created the data"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The impact to the organization if the data's confidentiality, integrity, or availability is compromised</strong> — classification should be driven by business impact and sensitivity, ensuring protection is proportional to potential harm.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The file format in which the data is stored</b>: format is a technical attribute unrelated to sensitivity or impact.</span><span class='qd'><b>The age of the data set</b>: age may be a factor in retention decisions but does not by itself determine sensitivity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The department that originally created the data</b>: ownership matters for accountability but not for determining the impact-based classification level.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-017","domain":3,"obj":"3A5","diff":"easy","q":"Who is typically MOST responsible for assigning the classification level of a specific business data asset?","options":["The data owner","The help desk technician","The network administrator","The external auditor"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The data owner</strong> — the business owner understands the data's value and sensitivity and is accountable for assigning its classification and approving access.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The help desk technician</b>: provides operational support but lacks the business context to classify data.</span><span class='qd'><b>The network administrator</b>: manages technical infrastructure, not the business decision of data sensitivity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The external auditor</b>: assesses compliance with classification policy but does not assign classifications.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-018","domain":3,"obj":"3A5","diff":"easy","q":"An asset inventory used for security program planning should PRIMARILY include which attribute to support risk-based prioritization?","options":["Purchase order number","Asset color or physical appearance","Business criticality and data classification","The vendor's marketing name for the product"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Business criticality and data classification</strong> — these attributes allow the security program to prioritize protection and resources according to the risk each asset represents to the business.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Purchase order number</b>: useful for procurement tracking but irrelevant to risk prioritization.</span><span class='qd'><b>Asset color or physical appearance</b>: has no bearing on security risk or criticality.</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor's marketing name for the product</b>: branding information does not indicate the asset's importance to the business.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-019","domain":3,"obj":"3A6","diff":"hard","q":"Which metric would BEST demonstrate to executive management the operational effectiveness of the vulnerability management process?","options":["Total number of security policies published","Number of firewalls deployed","Mean time to remediate critical vulnerabilities","Number of employees in the security department"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Mean time to remediate critical vulnerabilities</strong> — this outcome-based metric directly reflects how effectively the organization identifies and closes high-risk exposures, which is meaningful to executives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Total number of security policies published</b>: a volume metric that says nothing about operational risk reduction.</span><span class='qd'><b>Number of firewalls deployed</b>: a count of assets, not a measure of process effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Number of employees in the security department</b>: staffing levels do not indicate how well vulnerabilities are managed.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-020","domain":3,"obj":"3A6","diff":"hard","q":"A security manager is selecting key risk indicators (KRIs) for a board-level dashboard. Which characteristic is MOST important for an effective KRI?","options":["It should be extremely technical so specialists appreciate its precision","It should change infrequently so reporting is simple","It should provide early warning of increasing risk exposure and be actionable by leadership","It should focus solely on compliance checklist completion"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>It should provide early warning of increasing risk exposure and be actionable by leadership</strong> — effective KRIs give leading indication of emerging risk in business terms so leadership can intervene before impact materializes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It should be extremely technical so specialists appreciate its precision</b>: board-level metrics must be understandable and decision-relevant to non-technical executives.</span><span class='qd'><b>It should change infrequently so reporting is simple</b>: a KRI that rarely changes provides little early-warning value.</span><span class='qd'><b>It should focus solely on compliance checklist completion</b>: compliance completion is a lagging, narrow measure and does not capture broader risk trends.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-021","domain":3,"obj":"3A6","diff":"easy","q":"An organization wants to measure the maturity of its information security program over time. Which approach is MOST appropriate?","options":["Compare the program against a recognized maturity model at defined intervals","Count the number of security incidents each quarter only","Survey employees once about whether they feel secure","Measure only the size of the security budget"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Compare the program against a recognized maturity model at defined intervals</strong> — maturity models (such as CMMI-based approaches) provide a structured, repeatable way to assess capability progression across defined domains over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Count the number of security incidents each quarter only</b>: incident counts reflect outcomes but not the underlying maturity of processes and capabilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Survey employees once about whether they feel secure</b>: a one-time subjective survey does not provide a structured or repeatable maturity measure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Measure only the size of the security budget</b>: spending level does not equate to program capability or effectiveness.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-022","domain":3,"obj":"3A7","diff":"hard","q":"When building the information security program budget, which approach BEST justifies requested funding to senior management?","options":["Requesting an arbitrary percentage increase over the prior year with no explanation","Matching whatever the largest competitor spends on security","Tying funding requests to identified risks, business objectives, and expected risk reduction","Requesting the maximum amount allowed by finance policy"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Tying funding requests to identified risks, business objectives, and expected risk reduction</strong> — budget justifications grounded in risk and business alignment are more persuasive and defensible to executives who must allocate limited resources.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Requesting an arbitrary percentage increase over the prior year with no explanation</b>: lacks the risk-based justification decision-makers require.</span><span class='qd'><b>Matching whatever the largest competitor spends on security</b>: competitor spending does not reflect the organization's own risk profile or needs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Requesting the maximum amount allowed by finance policy</b>: maximizing the ask without justification undermines credibility and proper stewardship.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-023","domain":3,"obj":"3A7","diff":"easy","q":"Which resource-management activity MOST directly supports ensuring the security program has staff with the right skills for planned initiatives?","options":["Vulnerability scanning","Patch management","Workforce and skills-gap planning","Network segmentation"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Workforce and skills-gap planning</strong> — assessing current staff competencies against program needs and planning hiring, training, or outsourcing directly addresses resource adequacy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Vulnerability scanning</b>: a technical control activity, not a resource-planning function.</span><span class='qd'><b>Patch management</b>: an operational process unrelated to staffing and skills planning.</span><span class='qd'><b>Network segmentation</b>: an architectural control, not a human-resource planning activity.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-024","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"easy","q":"Which control category includes policies, standards, and organizational processes rather than physical or technical mechanisms?","options":["Technical controls","Physical controls","Managerial (administrative) controls","Detective controls"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Managerial (administrative) controls</strong> — these controls consist of governance mechanisms such as policies, standards, procedures, and organizational processes that direct behavior and decision-making.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Technical controls</b>: implemented through hardware or software mechanisms, such as firewalls or encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical controls</b>: tangible measures like locks, fences, and guards that protect physical premises.</span><span class='qd'><b>Detective controls</b>: this describes a control type by function (identifying events), not a control category.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-025","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"easy","q":"A badge reader that unlocks a data center door only after validating an employee's credential is an example of which control category?","options":["Managerial control","Operational control","Physical control","Compensating control"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Physical control</strong> — a badge reader is a tangible mechanism that restricts physical access to a facility or space.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Managerial control</b>: managerial controls are governance-oriented (policies, standards), not physical mechanisms.</span><span class='qd'><b>Operational control</b>: operational controls are the day-to-day processes people perform, distinct from a physical access device.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compensating control</b>: this describes a control's functional role as an alternative to a primary control, not its category.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-026","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"hard","q":"Security awareness training delivered by staff who follow a documented onboarding checklist is BEST classified as which control category?","options":["Technical control","Physical control","Operational control","Detective control (by category)"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Operational control</strong> — controls executed by people through day-to-day operational processes, such as delivering training per a checklist, fall into the operational category.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Technical control</b>: technical controls are enforced through technology, not human-performed processes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical control</b>: physical controls protect tangible spaces and assets, not training delivery.</span><span class='qd'><b>Detective control (by category)</b>: detective is a functional type, not a control category, and training here is preventive in nature, not detective.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-027","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"easy","q":"An intrusion detection system (IDS) that alerts on suspicious network traffic is an example of which control type?","options":["Preventive","Deterrent","Detective","Corrective"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Detective</strong> — an IDS identifies and alerts on potentially malicious activity after it occurs, rather than blocking it, making it a detective control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Preventive</b>: preventive controls stop an event from occurring, such as an intrusion prevention system actively blocking traffic.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deterrent</b>: deterrent controls discourage bad behavior through perceived consequences, not real-time detection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective</b>: corrective controls act after an incident to restore or fix systems, not to detect activity.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-028","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"easy","q":"Restoring a system from a clean backup after a malware infection is an example of which control type?","options":["Preventive","Detective","Corrective","Deterrent"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Corrective</strong> — corrective controls act after an incident to restore systems and data to a known-good state, limiting the extent of damage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Preventive</b>: preventive controls aim to stop the malware infection before it happens.</span><span class='qd'><b>Detective</b>: detective controls identify that the infection occurred, but restoring from backup is a remediation action.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deterrent</b>: deterrent controls discourage the attack attempt, unrelated to post-incident restoration.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-029","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"easy","q":"A warning banner displayed at system logon stating that unauthorized access is prohibited and monitored is PRIMARILY which control type?","options":["Deterrent","Corrective","Detective","Compensating"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Deterrent</strong> — the banner is intended to discourage potential attackers by communicating that unauthorized activity is prohibited and monitored, influencing behavior before an attempt occurs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective</b>: corrective controls act after an incident to fix or restore, not to discourage attempts beforehand.</span><span class='qd'><b>Detective</b>: the banner itself does not detect activity; it only communicates a warning.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compensating</b>: compensating controls substitute for an unavailable primary control, which does not describe a warning banner's function.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-030","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"hard","q":"An organization cannot immediately patch a critical vulnerability in a legacy application due to vendor constraints. The security manager implements enhanced network monitoring and strict access restrictions around the system instead. This is an example of which control type?","options":["Preventive control replacing the need for patching","Deterrent control with no real protective value","Compensating control mitigating risk until remediation is possible","Corrective control that fixes the vulnerability"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Compensating control mitigating risk until remediation is possible</strong> — when the primary control (patching) cannot be applied, an alternative control that reduces risk to an acceptable level is implemented, which is the definition of a compensating control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Preventive control replacing the need for patching</b>: monitoring and access restriction reduce exposure but do not eliminate the vulnerability the way a preventive fix would.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deterrent control with no real protective value</b>: enhanced monitoring and access restriction have measurable protective and detective value, not merely deterrent value.</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective control that fixes the vulnerability</b>: the vulnerability itself remains unpatched; these measures only reduce risk of exploitation.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-031","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"easy","q":"When selecting a control to address an identified risk, which factor should the security manager evaluate FIRST?","options":["Whether the control is the newest technology available","Whether competitors use the same control","Whether the control's cost and impact are proportionate to the risk it mitigates","Whether the control vendor offers the lowest price"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Whether the control's cost and impact are proportionate to the risk it mitigates</strong> — control selection should be risk-based and cost-effective, ensuring the level of protection matches the value being protected.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Whether the control is the newest technology available</b>: novelty does not guarantee suitability or proportionate risk reduction.</span><span class='qd'><b>Whether competitors use the same control</b>: peer practice may inform decisions but does not substitute for the organization's own risk-based analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>Whether the control vendor offers the lowest price</b>: price alone ignores whether the control adequately addresses the risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-032","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"easy","q":"A security manager is choosing between two controls that both reduce a given risk to an acceptable level. Which criterion should MOST influence the final selection?","options":["The control with the highest total cost of ownership","The control that is most difficult to implement","The control that provides the best cost-benefit ratio and fits existing operational capability","The control preferred by the vendor's sales representative"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The control that provides the best cost-benefit ratio and fits existing operational capability</strong> — when two controls achieve equivalent risk reduction, efficiency and operational fit should drive the decision to optimize resource use.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The control with the highest total cost of ownership</b>: higher cost without added benefit is an inefficient use of resources.</span><span class='qd'><b>The control that is most difficult to implement</b>: unnecessary complexity increases risk of implementation failure without added value.</span><span class='qd'><b>The control preferred by the vendor's sales representative</b>: vendor preference is not an objective basis for selection.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-033","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"easy","q":"Before deploying a new control into production, which activity is MOST important to confirm the control operates as intended?","options":["Announcing the control in a company newsletter","Filing the control description in the asset inventory","Conducting control testing, such as functional and user acceptance testing","Waiting for the next annual audit to validate it"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Conducting control testing, such as functional and user acceptance testing</strong> — testing before production deployment verifies the control performs its intended function and does not introduce unintended issues.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Announcing the control in a company newsletter</b>: communication is useful but does not validate technical effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Filing the control description in the asset inventory</b>: documentation supports tracking but does not verify functionality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Waiting for the next annual audit to validate it</b>: delaying validation until an annual audit leaves the control unverified for an extended period, risking undetected failures.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-034","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"hard","q":"After implementing a new data loss prevention (DLP) control, periodic testing reveals a high rate of false positives that is overwhelming the security operations team. What is the MOST appropriate NEXT step?","options":["Disable the DLP control entirely until further notice","Ignore the false positives since some noise is expected","Tune the DLP rules and thresholds based on the testing results to reduce false positives while maintaining detection effectiveness","Reassign all false positive alerts to end users to resolve"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Tune the DLP rules and thresholds based on the testing results to reduce false positives while maintaining detection effectiveness</strong> — control testing exists to surface exactly this kind of tuning need; adjusting rules improves signal quality without abandoning the control's protective purpose.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable the DLP control entirely until further notice</b>: removes protection against data loss altogether, an overreaction to a tuning problem.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore the false positives since some noise is expected</b>: unaddressed alert fatigue can cause the team to miss genuine incidents.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reassign all false positive alerts to end users to resolve</b>: end users are not equipped to triage security alerts, and this abdicates the security team's responsibility.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-035","domain":3,"obj":"3B5","diff":"easy","q":"The principle of granting users only the access necessary to perform their job duties is known as:","options":["Separation of duties","Mandatory access control","Least privilege","Single sign-on"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Least privilege</strong> — this principle restricts each user's access rights to the minimum necessary to perform authorized tasks, reducing the potential impact of error or compromise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Separation of duties</b>: divides critical tasks among multiple people to prevent a single individual from completing a sensitive process alone.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mandatory access control</b>: an access model where access decisions are made by a central authority based on classification labels, not the minimal-access principle itself.</span><span class='qd'><b>Single sign-on</b>: an authentication convenience feature unrelated to limiting privilege scope.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-036","domain":3,"obj":"3B5","diff":"easy","q":"Which access control model assigns permissions to users based on their job function within the organization?","options":["Discretionary access control (DAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)","Role-based access control (RBAC)","Rule-based access control only"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Role-based access control (RBAC)</strong> — RBAC grants permissions according to predefined roles that align with job functions, simplifying administration and enforcing consistent access.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Discretionary access control (DAC)</b>: resource owners decide who gets access, independent of formal job-function roles.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mandatory access control (MAC)</b>: access is dictated by a central authority using classification labels, not job roles.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rule-based access control only</b>: access decisions follow explicit rules (e.g., time-of-day) rather than job-function role assignment.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-037","domain":3,"obj":"3B5","diff":"med","q":"An organization wants access decisions to consider multiple dynamic attributes, such as user department, device compliance status, and location, rather than a fixed role alone. Which access control model BEST fits this requirement?","options":["Role-based access control (RBAC)","Discretionary access control (DAC)","Attribute-based access control (ABAC)","Rule of two-person control"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Attribute-based access control (ABAC)</strong> — ABAC evaluates multiple attributes (user, resource, environment) dynamically to make fine-grained, context-aware access decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Role-based access control (RBAC)</b>: RBAC ties permissions to static roles and does not natively factor in dynamic context like device compliance or location.</span><span class='qd'><b>Discretionary access control (DAC)</b>: access is left to the discretion of resource owners rather than governed by multi-attribute policy evaluation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rule of two-person control</b>: a specific control requiring two individuals to complete an action, not a general access control model.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-038","domain":3,"obj":"3B5","diff":"med","q":"Requiring that the person who initiates a wire transfer cannot also be the person who approves it is an example of:","options":["Least privilege","Job rotation","Separation of duties","Mandatory vacation"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Separation of duties</strong> — dividing initiation and approval responsibilities between different people prevents a single individual from committing and concealing fraud.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: limits the scope of access an individual has but does not specifically require splitting a process between two people.</span><span class='qd'><b>Job rotation</b>: periodically moves staff between roles to surface irregularities over time, not a real-time dual-control requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mandatory vacation</b>: forces time away from duties to help reveal fraud, distinct from splitting a transaction between two roles.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-039","domain":3,"obj":"3B6","diff":"easy","q":"Which authentication approach requires a user to provide two or more independent credential types, such as a password and a one-time code?","options":["Single sign-on","Federated identity","Multi-factor authentication (MFA)","Discretionary access control"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Multi-factor authentication (MFA)</strong> — MFA strengthens authentication assurance by requiring two or more independent factors (something you know, have, or are).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Single sign-on</b>: allows one authentication event to grant access to multiple systems, but does not itself require multiple factors.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federated identity</b>: allows identity to be trusted across organizational boundaries, a separate concept from requiring multiple factors.</span><span class='qd'><b>Discretionary access control</b>: an access authorization model, not an authentication mechanism.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-040","domain":3,"obj":"3B6","diff":"med","q":"A privileged access management (PAM) solution provides which PRIMARY security benefit?","options":["It eliminates the need for network firewalls","It replaces the need for security awareness training","It vaults, monitors, and controls the use of administrative and other high-risk credentials","It automatically classifies data based on content"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>It vaults, monitors, and controls the use of administrative and other high-risk credentials</strong> — PAM solutions secure, rotate, and audit privileged account usage, reducing the risk associated with powerful credentials.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for network firewalls</b>: PAM is an identity control, unrelated to network perimeter defenses.</span><span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for security awareness training</b>: awareness training addresses human behavior broadly and is not replaced by PAM.</span><span class='qd'><b>It automatically classifies data based on content</b>: data classification is typically handled by DLP or data-classification tools, not PAM.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-041","domain":3,"obj":"3B6","diff":"hard","q":"An organization implementing PAM notices that several service accounts have standing administrative privileges used only during quarterly maintenance windows. Which PAM practice BEST addresses this finding?","options":["Grant the service accounts permanent domain administrator rights for convenience","Share a single privileged credential among all service accounts","Implement just-in-time privilege elevation so access is granted only during approved maintenance windows","Remove all privileges from the service accounts permanently"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Implement just-in-time privilege elevation so access is granted only during approved maintenance windows</strong> — just-in-time access grants elevated rights only when needed and automatically revokes them afterward, minimizing the standing attack surface.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Grant the service accounts permanent domain administrator rights for convenience</b>: this increases standing privilege and risk, the opposite of the desired outcome.</span><span class='qd'><b>Share a single privileged credential among all service accounts</b>: shared credentials destroy accountability and traceability of actions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove all privileges from the service accounts permanently</b>: this would break the legitimate quarterly maintenance function that requires elevated access.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-042","domain":3,"obj":"3B7","diff":"easy","q":"Which technology is PRIMARILY used to protect the confidentiality of data both at rest and in transit through mathematical transformation of the data?","options":["Data loss prevention (DLP)","Network segmentation","Vulnerability scanning","Cryptography"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Cryptography</strong> — cryptographic techniques such as encryption transform data so that it is unreadable without the correct key, protecting confidentiality at rest and in transit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data loss prevention (DLP)</b>: monitors and restricts data movement and exfiltration, but does not itself transform data mathematically.</span><span class='qd'><b>Network segmentation</b>: isolates network zones to limit exposure, unrelated to mathematical data transformation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vulnerability scanning</b>: identifies weaknesses in systems, not a confidentiality-protection mechanism.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-043","domain":3,"obj":"3B7","diff":"med","q":"In a public key infrastructure (PKI), what is the PRIMARY role of the certificate authority (CA)?","options":["To store end-user passwords in plaintext for recovery","To encrypt all network traffic on behalf of end users","To serve as the sole repository for symmetric session keys","To issue, sign, and revoke digital certificates that bind public keys to verified identities"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>To issue, sign, and revoke digital certificates that bind public keys to verified identities</strong> — the CA is the trusted entity that validates identity and issues digital certificates, enabling trust in public key exchanges.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To store end-user passwords in plaintext for recovery</b>: storing plaintext passwords is a poor practice and unrelated to a CA's function.</span><span class='qd'><b>To encrypt all network traffic on behalf of end users</b>: the CA issues certificates that enable encryption but does not itself perform bulk traffic encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>To serve as the sole repository for symmetric session keys</b>: session keys are typically negotiated between endpoints, not stored centrally by the CA.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-044","domain":3,"obj":"3B7","diff":"hard","q":"An organization discovers that an intermediate certificate authority's private key has been compromised. What is the MOST appropriate IMMEDIATE action?","options":["Ignore the compromise since the root CA remains secure","Wait until the certificates naturally expire","Change only the affected end users' passwords","Revoke the compromised intermediate certificate and all certificates it issued, then reissue from a trusted CA"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Revoke the compromised intermediate certificate and all certificates it issued, then reissue from a trusted CA</strong> — a compromised intermediate CA key undermines the trust chain for every certificate it signed, requiring prompt revocation and reissuance to restore trust.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore the compromise since the root CA remains secure</b>: the intermediate CA's compromise directly threatens every certificate it issued, regardless of root CA status.</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait until the certificates naturally expire</b>: leaves the organization exposed to certificate misuse for the remaining validity period.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change only the affected end users' passwords</b>: passwords are unrelated to the cryptographic trust chain compromised by the CA key exposure.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-045","domain":3,"obj":"3B7","diff":"med","q":"A DLP solution configured to block emails containing patterns matching credit card numbers is an example of which type of control?","options":["Preventive technical control","Physical control","Deterrent managerial control","Corrective operational control"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Preventive technical control</strong> — the DLP system actively blocks the action before sensitive data leaves the organization, making it both preventive in function and technical in category.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical control</b>: physical controls protect tangible spaces, not electronic data transmission.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deterrent managerial control</b>: this is an active technical block, not a governance-based deterrent.</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective operational control</b>: the block occurs before data leaves, which is preventive rather than a post-event correction.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-046","domain":3,"obj":"3B8","diff":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a security awareness and training program?","options":["To satisfy a one-time regulatory checkbox","To replace the need for technical controls","To generate revenue through certification fees","To reduce human-related risk by helping personnel recognize and appropriately respond to security threats"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>To reduce human-related risk by helping personnel recognize and appropriately respond to security threats</strong> — awareness and training programs build a security-conscious culture that reduces the likelihood of successful social engineering, errors, and policy violations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To satisfy a one-time regulatory checkbox</b>: treating training as a single compliance exercise undermines its ongoing risk-reduction purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>To replace the need for technical controls</b>: awareness training complements, but does not replace, technical and other controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>To generate revenue through certification fees</b>: training exists to reduce risk, not as a revenue source.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-047","domain":3,"obj":"3B8","diff":"med","q":"An organization notices that phishing click rates remain high despite an annual, generic security awareness course. What is the MOST effective improvement?","options":["Discontinue the training program since it is not working","Make the training mandatory only for the IT department","Extend the annual course length without changing its content","Increase training frequency and tailor content with role-based, scenario-driven modules, including phishing simulations"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Increase training frequency and tailor content with role-based, scenario-driven modules, including phishing simulations</strong> — more frequent, targeted, and practical training (including simulated phishing) reinforces learning and better changes behavior than a single generic annual session.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Discontinue the training program since it is not working</b>: removing training entirely would likely worsen outcomes rather than address the root cause of ineffective content.</span><span class='qd'><b>Make the training mandatory only for the IT department</b>: phishing threats target all employees, so narrowing scope leaves most of the organization exposed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Extend the annual course length without changing its content</b>: lengthening the same ineffective content is unlikely to improve engagement or retention.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-048","domain":3,"obj":"3B8","diff":"med","q":"Specialized security training for software developers on secure coding practices is an example of:","options":["General security awareness training","Physical security training","Vendor sales training","Role-based security training"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Role-based security training</strong> — training tailored to the specific responsibilities of a role, such as secure coding for developers, addresses risks unique to that function.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>General security awareness training</b>: broad training for all employees on common threats, not specialized technical content for a specific role.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical security training</b>: addresses physical safety and facility security, not secure coding.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor sales training</b>: unrelated to internal security skill development.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-049","domain":3,"obj":"3B9","diff":"med","q":"Before granting a third-party vendor access to sensitive systems, which activity is MOST important for the security manager to perform?","options":["Immediately grant access to expedite the vendor relationship","Rely solely on the vendor's self-reported marketing claims","Skip due diligence for vendors referred by an executive","Conduct a third-party risk assessment and ensure contractual security requirements are in place"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Conduct a third-party risk assessment and ensure contractual security requirements are in place</strong> — assessing the vendor's security posture and embedding requirements in the contract ensures risk is understood and managed before access is granted.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately grant access to expedite the vendor relationship</b>: skipping due diligence exposes the organization to unassessed third-party risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on the vendor's self-reported marketing claims</b>: unverified vendor claims are not a substitute for independent risk assessment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Skip due diligence for vendors referred by an executive</b>: an executive referral does not reduce the vendor's actual security risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-050","domain":3,"obj":"3B9","diff":"hard","q":"A critical cloud service provider notifies the organization of a subcontractor change that will process customer data in a new jurisdiction. What should the security manager do FIRST?","options":["Terminate the contract immediately without review","Ignore the notification since it is the vendor's responsibility","Approve the change automatically because the primary vendor's contract already covers it","Assess the data protection and regulatory implications of the new jurisdiction and subcontractor before approving the change"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Assess the data protection and regulatory implications of the new jurisdiction and subcontractor before approving the change</strong> — fourth-party and cross-border changes can introduce new legal, privacy, and risk exposures that must be evaluated before consent is given.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Terminate the contract immediately without review</b>: an abrupt termination without assessment may be an overreaction and disrupt business operations unnecessarily.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore the notification since it is the vendor's responsibility</b>: the organization remains accountable for the protection of its data regardless of subcontracting arrangements.</span><span class='qd'><b>Approve the change automatically because the primary vendor's contract already covers it</b>: existing contract terms may not adequately address new jurisdictional or subcontractor risks.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-051","domain":3,"obj":"3B9","diff":"med","q":"Which contractual clause is MOST important for allowing an organization to verify a third party's ongoing compliance with agreed security requirements?","options":["A right-to-audit clause","A marketing exclusivity clause","A most-favored-customer pricing clause","A clause limiting the contract term to one year"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A right-to-audit clause</strong> — this clause grants the organization or its designated auditors the contractual ability to verify the vendor's security controls and compliance over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A marketing exclusivity clause</b>: governs promotional arrangements, unrelated to security compliance verification.</span><span class='qd'><b>A most-favored-customer pricing clause</b>: addresses pricing terms, not security oversight.</span><span class='qd'><b>A clause limiting the contract term to one year</b>: contract duration does not provide a mechanism to verify security compliance.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-052","domain":3,"obj":"3B10","diff":"med","q":"When reporting information security program status to the board of directors, which approach is MOST effective?","options":["Present raw vulnerability scan output line by line","Focus exclusively on technical jargon to demonstrate expertise","Omit any negative findings to avoid concerning the board","Summarize risk posture, key metrics, and business impact in terms relevant to organizational objectives"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Summarize risk posture, key metrics, and business impact in terms relevant to organizational objectives</strong> — board communication should translate technical detail into business-relevant risk information that supports informed governance decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Present raw vulnerability scan output line by line</b>: overwhelming technical detail obscures the meaningful risk picture for a governance audience.</span><span class='qd'><b>Focus exclusively on technical jargon to demonstrate expertise</b>: jargon-heavy reporting fails to inform decision-makers who need business context.</span><span class='qd'><b>Omit any negative findings to avoid concerning the board</b>: withholding material risk information undermines the board's oversight responsibility and organizational transparency.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-053","domain":3,"obj":"3B10","diff":"easy","q":"The PRIMARY purpose of ongoing communication between the security manager and business unit leaders is to:","options":["Fulfill a purely administrative formality","Reduce the frequency of required security training","Eliminate the need for a security steering committee","Ensure security priorities remain aligned with business needs and risks are understood"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Ensure security priorities remain aligned with business needs and risks are understood</strong> — regular two-way communication keeps the security program relevant to evolving business priorities and builds shared understanding of risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Fulfill a purely administrative formality</b>: treating communication as a formality misses its substantive alignment purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduce the frequency of required security training</b>: communication with business leaders is unrelated to training frequency decisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need for a security steering committee</b>: communication supplements, rather than replaces, governance structures like a steering committee.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-054","domain":3,"obj":"3B11","diff":"med","q":"Which budgeting approach requires each program element to be justified from a zero base each cycle, rather than starting from the prior year's allocation?","options":["Incremental budgeting","Capital expenditure budgeting only","Historical trend budgeting","Zero-based budgeting"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Zero-based budgeting</strong> — this approach requires every expense to be justified from scratch each period, rather than assuming continuation of prior allocations, promoting rigorous prioritization.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incremental budgeting</b>: adjusts the prior year's budget by a percentage rather than justifying every item anew.</span><span class='qd'><b>Capital expenditure budgeting only</b>: refers to a budget category (long-term investments) rather than a justification methodology.</span><span class='qd'><b>Historical trend budgeting</b>: projects future budgets based on past spending patterns, not a from-scratch justification.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-055","domain":3,"obj":"3B11","diff":"med","q":"A security manager must decide between funding a new security tool or additional staff headcount within a constrained annual budget. Which factor should MOST influence this decision?","options":["Which option has a lower one-time cost regardless of ongoing value","Whichever option was requested most recently","Which option is easiest to procure administratively","Which option delivers the greatest risk reduction and sustainable value relative to total cost"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Which option delivers the greatest risk reduction and sustainable value relative to total cost</strong> — budget allocation decisions should be based on the overall value and risk-reduction return relative to total cost of ownership, not just upfront price or convenience.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Which option has a lower one-time cost regardless of ongoing value</b>: focusing only on initial cost ignores long-term value and total cost of ownership.</span><span class='qd'><b>Whichever option was requested most recently</b>: recency of request has no bearing on which option best serves the program's risk objectives.</span><span class='qd'><b>Which option is easiest to procure administratively</b>: procurement ease should not override the substantive risk-reduction analysis.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-056","domain":3,"obj":"3B12","diff":"med","q":"Which activity BEST supports continuous improvement of the information security program over time?","options":["Conducting periodic program reviews and updating controls based on lessons learned and evolving risk","Freezing all controls once initially implemented","Avoiding metrics so as not to reveal weaknesses","Relying solely on regulatory mandates for direction"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Conducting periodic program reviews and updating controls based on lessons learned and evolving risk</strong> — continuous improvement requires regularly reassessing the program against changing threats, incidents, and business needs and adjusting accordingly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Freezing all controls once initially implemented</b>: a static control set will not adapt to evolving threats or organizational change.</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoiding metrics so as not to reveal weaknesses</b>: hiding weaknesses prevents identification of improvement opportunities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Relying solely on regulatory mandates for direction</b>: compliance is a baseline, not a substitute for proactive, risk-driven improvement.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-057","domain":3,"obj":"3B12","diff":"hard","q":"A maturity assessment reveals that the security program's incident response capability is at an ad hoc level while other capabilities are at a managed level. What is the MOST appropriate NEXT step?","options":["Ignore the gap since other areas are performing well","Downgrade all other capabilities to match the ad hoc level for consistency","Discontinue maturity assessments since they reveal weaknesses","Develop a targeted improvement plan to formalize and mature incident response processes"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Develop a targeted improvement plan to formalize and mature incident response processes</strong> — maturity assessments are diagnostic tools meant to identify gaps so that resources can be directed toward the weakest capability areas.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore the gap since other areas are performing well</b>: an immature incident response capability represents a significant risk regardless of strength elsewhere.</span><span class='qd'><b>Downgrade all other capabilities to match the ad hoc level for consistency</b>: deliberately lowering mature capabilities would be counterproductive and increase overall risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Discontinue maturity assessments since they reveal weaknesses</b>: assessments are valuable precisely because they reveal areas needing improvement; discontinuing them removes visibility into risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-058","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"hard","q":"A newly hired security manager finds that the prior security strategy was never formally approved by executive management and lacks measurable objectives. What is the MOST appropriate FIRST action?","options":["Continue executing the existing plan without changes since it is already funded","Immediately purchase new security tools to demonstrate progress","Wait one full year before addressing the gap","Engage executive stakeholders to validate business alignment, then formalize and obtain approval for a revised strategy with measurable objectives"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Engage executive stakeholders to validate business alignment, then formalize and obtain approval for a revised strategy with measurable objectives</strong> — a strategy lacking executive endorsement and measurable goals cannot be effectively governed or resourced; securing alignment and formal approval is the foundational corrective step.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Continue executing the existing plan without changes since it is already funded</b>: perpetuating an unapproved, unmeasurable plan leaves the program without proper governance and accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately purchase new security tools to demonstrate progress</b>: acquiring tools before establishing strategic direction risks misaligned, wasted investment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait one full year before addressing the gap</b>: delaying correction of a fundamental governance gap unnecessarily prolongs program risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-059","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"med","q":"An organization operating in multiple regulated industries wants a single framework that helps map overlapping compliance obligations to a common set of controls. This need is BEST addressed by:","options":["Using a unified control framework with a cross-mapping to applicable regulations and standards","Creating a completely separate, unrelated control set for each regulation","Ignoring regulatory overlaps and treating each requirement independently","Selecting the cheapest available framework regardless of fit"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Using a unified control framework with a cross-mapping to applicable regulations and standards</strong> — a common control framework mapped to multiple regulatory requirements reduces duplication of effort and provides consistent, efficient compliance management.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Creating a completely separate, unrelated control set for each regulation</b>: duplicative control sets increase cost and administrative burden unnecessarily.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignoring regulatory overlaps and treating each requirement independently</b>: ignoring overlap leads to redundant work and inconsistent control implementation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Selecting the cheapest available framework regardless of fit</b>: cost alone does not ensure the framework adequately addresses the organization's compliance needs.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-060","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"med","q":"An acceptable use policy would MOST appropriately address which of the following?","options":["Specific cryptographic algorithm parameters for VPN tunnels","The exact configuration of firewall access control lists","The step-by-step process for restoring a server from backup","High-level expectations for appropriate use of organizational IT resources by employees"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>High-level expectations for appropriate use of organizational IT resources by employees</strong> — an acceptable use policy sets management's expectations at a policy level regarding appropriate use of systems and resources.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Specific cryptographic algorithm parameters for VPN tunnels</b>: this level of technical detail belongs in a standard, not a policy.</span><span class='qd'><b>The exact configuration of firewall access control lists</b>: configuration detail is operational and belongs in a procedure or configuration standard.</span><span class='qd'><b>The step-by-step process for restoring a server from backup</b>: this is a procedural task, not a policy-level statement.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-061","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"med","q":"An organization is designing layered controls for its e-commerce environment. Which combination BEST reflects a defense-in-depth approach?","options":["A single web application firewall as the only control","Relying only on strong passwords for all systems","Physical security controls alone at the data center","Perimeter firewall, network segmentation, web application firewall, endpoint protection, and monitoring working together"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Perimeter firewall, network segmentation, web application firewall, endpoint protection, and monitoring working together</strong> — combining multiple, complementary layers across network, application, and endpoint domains reflects genuine defense-in-depth.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single web application firewall as the only control</b>: a single control creates a single point of failure, contrary to layered defense.</span><span class='qd'><b>Relying only on strong passwords for all systems</b>: passwords alone address only authentication and leave other attack vectors unmitigated.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical security controls alone at the data center</b>: physical controls address only one layer and ignore network and application risks relevant to e-commerce.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-062","domain":3,"obj":"3A5","diff":"med","q":"A data classification scheme labels information as Public, Internal, Confidential, and Restricted. Which factor determines the handling requirements applied to a document labeled Restricted?","options":["The document's file size","The number of people who have already viewed it","The department's annual budget","The predefined handling requirements associated with the highest sensitivity classification"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The predefined handling requirements associated with the highest sensitivity classification</strong> — the classification scheme defines specific handling, storage, and transmission requirements tied to each label, and Restricted carries the most stringent controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The document's file size</b>: file size has no bearing on sensitivity or required handling controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of people who have already viewed it</b>: prior viewing does not determine the classification's handling requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>The department's annual budget</b>: budget is unrelated to how sensitive data must be handled.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-063","domain":3,"obj":"3A6","diff":"med","q":"A security dashboard reports \"98% of laptops have antivirus installed.\" Which additional metric would BEST complement this to indicate actual control effectiveness?","options":["The number of laptops purchased last quarter","The color scheme used in the dashboard","The brand of laptop manufacturer","The percentage of laptops with antivirus signatures updated within a defined period and successfully detecting test samples"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The percentage of laptops with antivirus signatures updated within a defined period and successfully detecting test samples</strong> — installation alone does not confirm the control is functioning effectively; currency of signatures and detection capability better indicate real protective effectiveness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of laptops purchased last quarter</b>: procurement volume is unrelated to control effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color scheme used in the dashboard</b>: a cosmetic detail with no bearing on security metrics.</span><span class='qd'><b>The brand of laptop manufacturer</b>: hardware brand does not indicate whether antivirus is functioning effectively.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-064","domain":3,"obj":"3A7","diff":"med","q":"A security manager is preparing a resource plan for the coming year. Which input is MOST relevant when forecasting staffing needs?","options":["The number of holidays in the calendar year","The average commute time of current employees","The color scheme of the new office","Planned program initiatives, expected workload, and current skills gaps"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Planned program initiatives, expected workload, and current skills gaps</strong> — staffing forecasts should be driven by the work the program must deliver and the skills required to deliver it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of holidays in the calendar year</b>: a minor scheduling factor, not a primary driver of staffing needs.</span><span class='qd'><b>The average commute time of current employees</b>: unrelated to determining the number or skills of staff needed.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color scheme of the new office</b>: an irrelevant facilities detail.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-065","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"hard","q":"An organization implements a policy requiring background checks for new hires in sensitive roles, paired with a technical control that disables new accounts until HR confirms the check is complete. Which statement BEST describes these two controls?","options":["Both are technical controls","Both are physical controls","The background check policy is a technical control while the account mechanism is a managerial control","The background check policy is a managerial control while the account-disabling mechanism is a technical control"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The background check policy is a managerial control while the account-disabling mechanism is a technical control</strong> — the policy establishes a governance requirement (managerial), while the automated account-hold mechanism enforces it through system functionality (technical).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Both are technical controls</b>: the background check requirement itself is a policy-driven, administrative process, not a technical mechanism.</span><span class='qd'><b>Both are physical controls</b>: neither control involves physical premises or tangible barriers.</span><span class='qd'><b>The background check policy is a technical control while the account mechanism is a managerial control</b>: this reverses the correct categorization of each control.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-066","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"med","q":"Security cameras recording activity at building entrances, which are reviewed only after an incident is reported, PRIMARILY function as which control type?","options":["Preventive","Corrective","Compensating","Detective"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Detective</strong> — the cameras record and allow identification of events after they occur, functioning as a detective control rather than actively preventing entry.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Preventive</b>: since footage is reviewed only after the fact, the cameras are not actively stopping unauthorized entry in real time.</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective</b>: reviewing footage does not itself restore or fix anything; it aids investigation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compensating</b>: there is no indication this is substituting for an unavailable primary control.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-067","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"hard","q":"During control selection for a new payment processing system, the security manager must balance regulatory requirements, cost, and user experience. Which approach BEST reflects sound control selection practice?","options":["Select the control with the lowest cost regardless of regulatory fit","Select controls based solely on user experience, ignoring compliance","Defer control selection indefinitely until zero risk remains","Select controls that satisfy mandatory regulatory requirements first, then optimize for cost-effectiveness and usability within that constraint"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Select controls that satisfy mandatory regulatory requirements first, then optimize for cost-effectiveness and usability within that constraint</strong> — regulatory requirements represent a non-negotiable floor, after which the manager can optimize remaining decisions for efficiency and usability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Select the control with the lowest cost regardless of regulatory fit</b>: ignoring regulatory obligations risks noncompliance and potential penalties.</span><span class='qd'><b>Select controls based solely on user experience, ignoring compliance</b>: usability cannot override mandatory legal or regulatory requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>Defer control selection indefinitely until zero risk remains</b>: zero risk is unattainable, and indefinite deferral leaves the system unprotected.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-068","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"med","q":"Which testing method involves attempting to exploit vulnerabilities in a system to validate whether existing controls can be bypassed?","options":["Penetration testing","Tabletop exercise","Business impact analysis","Control self-assessment survey"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Penetration testing</strong> — this method actively simulates attacks to determine whether controls can be circumvented, providing direct evidence of control effectiveness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Tabletop exercise</b>: a discussion-based simulation of a scenario, not an active technical exploitation attempt.</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis</b>: evaluates the impact of disruptions on business processes, not control bypass testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Control self-assessment survey</b>: relies on subjective self-reporting rather than active technical validation.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-069","domain":3,"obj":"3B5","diff":"hard","q":"An internal audit finds that several terminated employees still have active accounts with access to financial systems. Which underlying process failure MOST likely caused this?","options":["Excessive network bandwidth allocation","Overly restrictive least-privilege enforcement","Excessive use of multi-factor authentication","Inadequate deprovisioning as part of the identity and access management lifecycle"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Inadequate deprovisioning as part of the identity and access management lifecycle</strong> — timely removal of access upon termination is a core IAM lifecycle control; its failure directly explains active accounts for former employees.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Excessive network bandwidth allocation</b>: bandwidth is unrelated to account lifecycle management.</span><span class='qd'><b>Overly restrictive least-privilege enforcement</b>: restrictive privilege would reduce, not create, lingering excess access.</span><span class='qd'><b>Excessive use of multi-factor authentication</b>: MFA strengthens authentication and would not cause stale accounts to remain active.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-070","domain":3,"obj":"3B6","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of session timeout controls combined with MFA for privileged accounts?","options":["To reduce the window of opportunity for misuse of an unattended or compromised privileged session","To increase help desk password reset ticket volume","To eliminate the need for logging privileged activity","To allow privileged sessions to remain active indefinitely for convenience"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>To reduce the window of opportunity for misuse of an unattended or compromised privileged session</strong> — session timeouts combined with strong authentication limit how long a privileged session remains exploitable if left unattended or hijacked.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To increase help desk password reset ticket volume</b>: this would be an unwanted side effect, not the control's purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>To eliminate the need for logging privileged activity</b>: session timeout does not replace the need for activity logging and monitoring.</span><span class='qd'><b>To allow privileged sessions to remain active indefinitely for convenience</b>: this directly contradicts the purpose of a timeout control.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-071","domain":3,"obj":"3B7","diff":"med","q":"An organization wants to ensure that data stored in a cloud object storage service cannot be read by the cloud provider's own administrators. Which approach BEST achieves this?","options":["Rely on the provider's default server-side encryption with provider-managed keys","Disable all encryption to simplify access","Store the data in plaintext but restrict network access","Use client-side encryption with customer-managed keys before uploading data to the cloud"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Use client-side encryption with customer-managed keys before uploading data to the cloud</strong> — encrypting data before it reaches the provider, and retaining control of the keys, ensures the provider cannot access plaintext data even with administrative privileges.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely on the provider's default server-side encryption with provider-managed keys</b>: if the provider manages the keys, its administrators could potentially access the data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable all encryption to simplify access</b>: removing encryption entirely exposes data to anyone with storage access, including the provider.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store the data in plaintext but restrict network access</b>: network restrictions do not prevent access by the provider's own administrators with storage-level access.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-072","domain":3,"obj":"3B8","diff":"easy","q":"Phishing simulation exercises are MOST valuable because they:","options":["Guarantee zero future phishing incidents","Replace the need for technical email filtering controls","Are required only for the IT security team","Provide measurable, real-world data on employee susceptibility to social engineering and reinforce training"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Provide measurable, real-world data on employee susceptibility to social engineering and reinforce training</strong> — simulations offer objective metrics on employee behavior and create teachable moments that reinforce awareness training.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Guarantee zero future phishing incidents</b>: no training method can guarantee elimination of all future incidents.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace the need for technical email filtering controls</b>: simulations address human behavior and complement, rather than replace, technical filtering.</span><span class='qd'><b>Are required only for the IT security team</b>: phishing threats target the entire workforce, not just IT security staff.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-073","domain":3,"obj":"3B9","diff":"med","q":"An organization's cloud service provider experiences a security incident. Which document should PRIMARILY define the provider's obligation to notify the organization within a specified time frame?","options":["The provider's general marketing brochure","The contractual service level agreement or security addendum with breach notification terms","An informal verbal understanding between account managers","The provider's public press release policy"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The contractual service level agreement or security addendum with breach notification terms</strong> — formal contractual terms, including a security addendum, are the enforceable basis defining notification timelines and obligations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider's general marketing brochure</b>: marketing material is not a binding or enforceable contractual obligation.</span><span class='qd'><b>An informal verbal understanding between account managers</b>: verbal agreements are not reliably enforceable and lack documented specificity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider's public press release policy</b>: press release timing is discretionary and not a contractual notification commitment to the customer.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-074","domain":3,"obj":"3B10","diff":"med","q":"A CISO wants to improve cross-departmental support for a new security initiative. Which communication strategy is MOST likely to succeed?","options":["Sending a single mass email announcement with no follow-up","Engaging department leaders early, explaining business benefits, and addressing concerns through ongoing dialogue","Withholding details until the initiative is fully implemented","Mandating compliance without any explanation of purpose"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Engaging department leaders early, explaining business benefits, and addressing concerns through ongoing dialogue</strong> — early stakeholder engagement, framed around business value, builds buy-in and reduces resistance to change.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Sending a single mass email announcement with no follow-up</b>: one-way communication without dialogue rarely secures genuine support.</span><span class='qd'><b>Withholding details until the initiative is fully implemented</b>: lack of transparency breeds distrust and resistance once the initiative surfaces.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mandating compliance without any explanation of purpose</b>: unexplained mandates often generate resentment and passive resistance.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-075","domain":3,"obj":"3B11","diff":"hard","q":"A security manager must justify a multi-year investment in a security information and event management (SIEM) platform to the finance committee. Which approach BEST supports the business case?","options":["Present only the vendor's list price without further analysis","Present a total cost of ownership analysis alongside expected risk reduction, efficiency gains, and alignment to compliance obligations","Avoid quantifying benefits since security value cannot be measured","Compare only the color and branding of competing vendor dashboards"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Present a total cost of ownership analysis alongside expected risk reduction, efficiency gains, and alignment to compliance obligations</strong> — a comprehensive business case that ties cost to quantifiable risk reduction and operational benefit is most persuasive to a finance-focused audience.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Present only the vendor's list price without further analysis</b>: price alone does not justify value or return on investment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoid quantifying benefits since security value cannot be measured</b>: security value can and should be quantified using risk and efficiency metrics to support funding decisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compare only the color and branding of competing vendor dashboards</b>: cosmetic factors are irrelevant to a sound financial business case.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-076","domain":3,"obj":"3B12","diff":"med","q":"Lessons learned from a recent security incident are documented and used to update the incident response procedure. This activity BEST exemplifies:","options":["Risk transfer","Continuous improvement of the security program","Data classification","Separation of duties"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Continuous improvement of the security program</strong> — incorporating lessons learned into updated procedures is a core mechanism for maturing and strengthening the program over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk transfer</b>: shifts risk to a third party (e.g., insurance), unrelated to updating internal procedures.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification</b>: concerns labeling data sensitivity, not incident response process updates.</span><span class='qd'><b>Separation of duties</b>: an access control principle unrelated to procedural lessons-learned updates.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-077","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"med","q":"Which statement BEST reflects the relationship between the information security strategy and the enterprise's overall business strategy?","options":["The security strategy should be developed independently, with no reference to business strategy","The security strategy should derive from and support the achievement of business strategy and objectives","The business strategy should be modified to fit whatever security tools were previously purchased","Security strategy and business strategy address entirely unrelated aims"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The security strategy should derive from and support the achievement of business strategy and objectives</strong> — effective security strategy exists to enable and protect business goals, so it must be derived from and aligned with them.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The security strategy should be developed independently, with no reference to business strategy</b>: an independent strategy risks misalignment and wasted investment on priorities the business does not value.</span><span class='qd'><b>The business strategy should be modified to fit whatever security tools were previously purchased</b>: this backwards approach subordinates business direction to existing tooling rather than risk and value.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security strategy and business strategy address entirely unrelated aims</b>: security exists specifically to protect and enable business objectives, so the two are inherently connected.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-078","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a management framework focused on governance and management of enterprise IT, including control objectives that can support information security governance?","options":["COBIT","OWASP Top 10","CVSS","MITRE ATT&CK"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>COBIT</strong> — COBIT is a governance and management framework for enterprise IT that provides control objectives supporting alignment between IT (including security) and business goals.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>OWASP Top 10</b>: a list of common web application security risks, not an IT governance framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>CVSS</b>: a scoring system for rating the severity of vulnerabilities, not a governance framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>MITRE ATT&CK</b>: a knowledge base of adversary tactics and techniques, not a governance or management framework.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-079","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"hard","q":"A security manager finds that several departmental procedures conflict with the enterprise password standard, allowing shorter passwords for legacy convenience. What is the MOST appropriate resolution?","options":["Allow each department to maintain its own conflicting procedure indefinitely","Align the departmental procedures with the enterprise standard, applying compensating controls or a formal exception where technically justified","Delete the enterprise standard since departments disagree with it","Ignore the conflict since procedures are considered unimportant"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Align the departmental procedures with the enterprise standard, applying compensating controls or a formal exception where technically justified</strong> — procedures must support, not contradict, mandatory standards; where genuine technical constraints exist, a formal, risk-assessed exception process should be used.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Allow each department to maintain its own conflicting procedure indefinitely</b>: uncontrolled deviation undermines the enterprise standard and creates inconsistent risk exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete the enterprise standard since departments disagree with it</b>: abandoning a sound standard due to localized disagreement removes needed enterprise-wide protection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore the conflict since procedures are considered unimportant</b>: procedures that violate standards represent real control gaps that must be addressed.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-080","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"med","q":"Micro-segmentation within a data center is MOST accurately described as:","options":["A single flat network with no internal boundaries","Dividing the network into small, isolated zones to limit lateral movement between workloads","A physical security control for building entrances","A method for encrypting data at rest only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Dividing the network into small, isolated zones to limit lateral movement between workloads</strong> — micro-segmentation creates granular network boundaries between individual workloads or applications, restricting an attacker's ability to move laterally after an initial compromise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single flat network with no internal boundaries</b>: this describes the opposite of segmentation, which increases lateral movement risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>A physical security control for building entrances</b>: micro-segmentation is a network architecture concept, not a physical access control.</span><span class='qd'><b>A method for encrypting data at rest only</b>: encryption protects data confidentiality but is unrelated to network zone isolation.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-081","domain":3,"obj":"3A5","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's data classification policy has not been updated in five years, and new types of data (e.g., biometric templates) are now collected without a defined classification. What is the MOST appropriate action?","options":["Leave the unclassified data as is since the policy predates its collection","Review and update the classification scheme to address new data types and reclassify accordingly","Automatically classify all new data types as Public by default","Delete all biometric data to avoid the classification question"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Review and update the classification scheme to address new data types and reclassify accordingly</strong> — classification schemes must evolve to cover new data types as they are collected, ensuring appropriate protection based on actual sensitivity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Leave the unclassified data as is since the policy predates its collection</b>: unclassified sensitive data remains unprotected and out of policy scope, which is a governance gap.</span><span class='qd'><b>Automatically classify all new data types as Public by default</b>: biometric data is highly sensitive and defaulting to Public would grossly under-protect it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete all biometric data to avoid the classification question</b>: deletion may not be feasible or desirable if the data supports a legitimate business purpose; the real fix is proper classification and controls.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-082","domain":3,"obj":"3A6","diff":"med","q":"An effective security scorecard for executive reporting should PRIMARILY translate technical data into:","options":["Raw log file excerpts","Business-relevant risk and performance indicators","Vendor product feature lists","Individual employee performance reviews"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Business-relevant risk and performance indicators</strong> — executive audiences need metrics translated into business impact and risk terms to make informed decisions and allocate resources appropriately.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Raw log file excerpts</b>: raw technical data is not digestible or meaningful for an executive audience.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor product feature lists</b>: irrelevant to demonstrating program performance or risk posture.</span><span class='qd'><b>Individual employee performance reviews</b>: personnel evaluations are a separate HR function, not a security scorecard element.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-083","domain":3,"obj":"3A7","diff":"hard","q":"Due to budget cuts, the security manager must reduce planned initiatives for the coming year. Which approach BEST preserves the organization's risk posture?","options":["Cut initiatives randomly to meet the reduced budget quickly","Reassess the risk register and prioritize funding for initiatives addressing the highest residual risk, deferring lower-priority items","Cancel all security awareness training first regardless of its risk contribution","Cut monitoring and logging capabilities first since they produce no visible output"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Reassess the risk register and prioritize funding for initiatives addressing the highest residual risk, deferring lower-priority items</strong> — under budget constraints, a risk-based reprioritization ensures the most significant exposures remain addressed while lower-impact initiatives are deferred.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cut initiatives randomly to meet the reduced budget quickly</b>: random cuts may eliminate high-value, high-risk-reduction initiatives while preserving low-value ones.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cancel all security awareness training first regardless of its risk contribution</b>: eliminating training without risk analysis may remove a cost-effective control against a major threat vector.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cut monitoring and logging capabilities first since they produce no visible output</b>: monitoring and logging are critical for detection and incident response; assuming they have no value is a flawed premise.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-084","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"med","q":"A quarterly access recertification process performed by managers to confirm employees still require their current access is BEST classified as which control category?","options":["Technical control","Operational (administrative process) control","Physical control","Deterrent-only control"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Operational (administrative process) control</strong> — the recertification is a recurring, people-driven process performed as part of normal operations to validate access appropriateness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Technical control</b>: unless automated end-to-end, a manager-driven recertification is fundamentally a process activity, not a technology mechanism.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical control</b>: unrelated to physical premises or tangible barriers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deterrent-only control</b>: this describes a control's functional type, and recertification is more accurately detective/corrective in function, not merely deterrent.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-085","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"med","q":"Mantraps installed at a data center entrance that only allow one person to pass after successful badge and biometric verification PRIMARILY serve as which control type?","options":["Preventive","Corrective","Detective","Compensating"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Preventive</strong> — mantraps actively stop unauthorized individuals, including tailgaters, from physically entering before verification succeeds, making them a preventive control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Corrective</b>: corrective controls act after an incident to remediate; a mantrap acts proactively to prevent entry.</span><span class='qd'><b>Detective</b>: detective controls identify events after they happen, whereas the mantrap blocks unauthorized entry in real time.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compensating</b>: there is no indication this substitutes for an unavailable primary control; it functions as a primary preventive measure.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-086","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"med","q":"When two candidate controls provide similar risk reduction but one significantly degrades system performance and user productivity, which consideration should the security manager weigh MOST heavily?","options":["Ignore usability entirely since security always takes precedence","Balance security benefit against operational impact to select the control that provides acceptable protection with manageable business disruption","Automatically choose the more expensive control assuming higher cost means better security","Select the control at random since both reduce risk equally"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Balance security benefit against operational impact to select the control that provides acceptable protection with manageable business disruption</strong> — effective control selection weighs both risk reduction and business/operational impact to find a sustainable, practical solution.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore usability entirely since security always takes precedence</b>: excessive business disruption can lead to workarounds that undermine the control's effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Automatically choose the more expensive control assuming higher cost means better security</b>: cost does not necessarily correlate with effectiveness or fit for the environment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Select the control at random since both reduce risk equally</b>: random selection ignores the material difference in operational impact between the two options.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-087","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"med","q":"A tabletop exercise simulating a ransomware attack is PRIMARILY used to:","options":["Physically test backup hardware performance under load","Validate and improve the effectiveness of response plans, roles, and communication through discussion-based simulation","Replace the need for technical penetration testing entirely","Certify compliance with encryption standards"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Validate and improve the effectiveness of response plans, roles, and communication through discussion-based simulation</strong> — tabletop exercises walk stakeholders through a simulated scenario to test decision-making, coordination, and plan adequacy without live system impact.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Physically test backup hardware performance under load</b>: tabletop exercises are discussion-based, not technical performance tests.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace the need for technical penetration testing entirely</b>: tabletop exercises complement, but do not replace, technical testing methods like penetration testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certify compliance with encryption standards</b>: unrelated to the exercise's purpose of testing response coordination.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-088","domain":3,"obj":"3B5","diff":"med","q":"An organization implementing RBAC finds that many users have been granted additional, ad hoc permissions beyond their assigned role over time. This condition is BEST described as:","options":["Least privilege","Privilege creep","Job rotation","Federation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Privilege creep</strong> — this term describes the gradual accumulation of unnecessary access rights over time, typically due to role changes or ad hoc grants that are never revoked.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: describes the desired minimal-access state, which is the opposite of what is occurring here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Job rotation</b>: a control practice of moving staff between roles, not a description of unchecked permission accumulation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federation</b>: refers to trusting identities across organizational boundaries, unrelated to accumulating excess permissions.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-089","domain":3,"obj":"3B6","diff":"med","q":"An organization wants to allow employees to authenticate once and gain access to multiple trusted applications without re-entering credentials for each. Which technology BEST supports this?","options":["Single sign-on (SSO)","Mandatory access control","Data loss prevention","Network access control lists"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Single sign-on (SSO)</strong> — SSO enables a single authentication event to grant access across multiple integrated applications, improving both usability and centralized control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Mandatory access control</b>: an authorization model based on classification labels, not an authentication convenience mechanism.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data loss prevention</b>: focuses on preventing unauthorized data exfiltration, unrelated to authentication across applications.</span><span class='qd'><b>Network access control lists</b>: govern network traffic permissions, not user authentication across applications.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-090","domain":3,"obj":"3B7","diff":"med","q":"Which key management practice BEST reduces the risk of a single compromised cryptographic key exposing all historical encrypted communications?","options":["Reusing the same key indefinitely for all sessions","Implementing forward secrecy through regularly rotated ephemeral session keys","Storing all keys in a single unprotected shared file","Publishing private keys to a public repository for convenience"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Implementing forward secrecy through regularly rotated ephemeral session keys</strong> — forward secrecy ensures that compromise of one session's key does not expose the content of past or future sessions, since each session uses a unique, short-lived key.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reusing the same key indefinitely for all sessions</b>: a single long-lived key, if compromised, would expose all data ever encrypted with it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing all keys in a single unprotected shared file</b>: this practice increases the likelihood of compromise rather than reducing exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Publishing private keys to a public repository for convenience</b>: exposing private keys publicly completely defeats the purpose of cryptographic protection.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-091","domain":3,"obj":"3B8","diff":"med","q":"Which metric would BEST measure the effectiveness of an organization's security awareness program over time?","options":["The number of posters displayed in office break rooms","Trend in simulated phishing click-through and reporting rates across successive campaigns","The total budget spent on training materials","The number of training vendors evaluated"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Trend in simulated phishing click-through and reporting rates across successive campaigns</strong> — tracking behavioral trends over multiple simulations provides a direct, outcome-based measure of whether awareness efforts are changing employee behavior.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of posters displayed in office break rooms</b>: an output metric with no connection to actual behavior change.</span><span class='qd'><b>The total budget spent on training materials</b>: spending level does not indicate whether the training is effective.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of training vendors evaluated</b>: a procurement activity metric, not a measure of program effectiveness.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-092","domain":3,"obj":"3B9","diff":"med","q":"An organization's vendor risk management program should PRIMARILY classify vendors based on:","options":["Alphabetical order of vendor company name","The level of access to sensitive data or critical systems and the potential impact of a vendor failure","The vendor's geographic headquarters only","The number of years the vendor has existed"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The level of access to sensitive data or critical systems and the potential impact of a vendor failure</strong> — tiering vendors by risk exposure and potential business impact allows the organization to apply proportionate due diligence and monitoring.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Alphabetical order of vendor company name</b>: an arbitrary ordering with no relationship to actual risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor's geographic headquarters only</b>: location may be one input for regulatory considerations but is not the primary risk-tiering factor.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of years the vendor has existed</b>: longevity alone does not indicate the risk associated with the vendor's access or services.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-093","domain":3,"obj":"3B10","diff":"med","q":"Following a significant security incident, which type of communication should the security manager PRIORITIZE with executive leadership?","options":["A purely technical packet capture analysis with no summary","Timely, clear updates on business impact, response status, and key decisions needed from leadership","No communication until the incident is fully closed months later","A social media post describing full technical details of the exploit"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Timely, clear updates on business impact, response status, and key decisions needed from leadership</strong> — during and after an incident, executives need concise, business-relevant updates to make informed decisions and fulfill oversight responsibilities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A purely technical packet capture analysis with no summary</b>: overly technical detail without business context is not actionable for executives.</span><span class='qd'><b>No communication until the incident is fully closed months later</b>: delaying communication for months deprives leadership of the timely information needed to manage the situation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A social media post describing full technical details of the exploit</b>: publicly disclosing exploit details could aid attackers and is not an appropriate executive communication channel.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-094","domain":3,"obj":"3B11","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the MOST appropriate justification for including contingency (reserve) funds in the security program budget?","options":["To pad the budget for unrelated departmental expenses","To provide flexibility to respond to unforeseen incidents or emerging risks during the budget cycle","To guarantee year-end bonuses for the security team","To avoid ever having to request additional funding in the future"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To provide flexibility to respond to unforeseen incidents or emerging risks during the budget cycle</strong> — contingency funds allow the program to respond promptly to unplanned security events or newly emerging risks without lengthy budget re-approval delays.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To pad the budget for unrelated departmental expenses</b>: reserve funds should be reserved for legitimate security contingencies, not unrelated spending.</span><span class='qd'><b>To guarantee year-end bonuses for the security team</b>: compensation decisions are a separate HR function, not the purpose of a risk contingency reserve.</span><span class='qd'><b>To avoid ever having to request additional funding in the future</b>: a contingency reserve manages near-term unforeseen needs, not a substitute for future budget planning.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-095","domain":3,"obj":"3B12","diff":"med","q":"An organization benchmarks its security program annually against industry peers using a maturity model. What is the PRIMARY benefit of this practice?","options":["It guarantees regulatory compliance automatically","It identifies relative strengths and gaps, informing targeted investment and improvement priorities","It eliminates the need for internal risk assessments","It replaces the need for a security strategy"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It identifies relative strengths and gaps, informing targeted investment and improvement priorities</strong> — benchmarking against peers and maturity models highlights where the program lags or excels, guiding where to focus improvement efforts and resources.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees regulatory compliance automatically</b>: maturity benchmarking does not by itself ensure compliance with specific legal or regulatory requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for internal risk assessments</b>: benchmarking is a complementary practice, not a replacement for organization-specific risk assessment.</span><span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for a security strategy</b>: benchmarking informs strategy but does not substitute for having one.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-096","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST indicates that an information security program has strong executive sponsorship?","options":["The security manager independently approves the entire program budget without oversight","Senior leadership actively participates in governance forums, approves strategy, and allocates adequate resources","The program operates without any documented charter or reporting line","Security decisions are made solely by external consultants"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Senior leadership actively participates in governance forums, approves strategy, and allocates adequate resources</strong> — genuine executive sponsorship is demonstrated through active governance participation, strategic approval, and resource commitment, not just nominal endorsement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The security manager independently approves the entire program budget without oversight</b>: lack of oversight is a governance weakness, not evidence of sponsorship.</span><span class='qd'><b>The program operates without any documented charter or reporting line</b>: absence of a charter indicates weak, not strong, governance and sponsorship.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security decisions are made solely by external consultants</b>: outsourcing all decision-making to consultants does not reflect internal executive sponsorship.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-097","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"med","q":"An organization mapping its controls to both ISO/IEC 27002 and NIST CSF finds significant overlap. What is the MOST efficient way to manage this overlap going forward?","options":["Maintain two entirely separate and duplicated control documentation sets forever","Build a unified control set with a cross-reference matrix mapping each control to both frameworks","Abandon both frameworks and use no formal reference","Choose the framework with the shortest document length only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Build a unified control set with a cross-reference matrix mapping each control to both frameworks</strong> — a single control set with cross-mapping avoids duplicate effort while still satisfying reporting or certification needs tied to each framework.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Maintain two entirely separate and duplicated control documentation sets forever</b>: duplication wastes effort and increases the risk of inconsistency between the two sets.</span><span class='qd'><b>Abandon both frameworks and use no formal reference</b>: dropping structured frameworks removes valuable, recognized guidance without justification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Choose the framework with the shortest document length only</b>: document length is irrelevant to which framework(s) best serve organizational needs.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-098","domain":3,"obj":"3A5","diff":"med","q":"A merger brings a newly acquired company's IT assets into scope for the information security program. What should be done FIRST regarding these assets?","options":["Assume they meet existing classification and control standards without verification","Inventory and classify the acquired assets, then assess their security posture against the organization's standards","Immediately decommission all acquired systems without assessment","Grant unrestricted network access to all acquired systems"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Inventory and classify the acquired assets, then assess their security posture against the organization's standards</strong> — newly acquired assets must be identified, classified, and evaluated before they can be safely integrated and appropriately protected.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume they meet existing classification and control standards without verification</b>: assuming compliance without verification risks undetected gaps and vulnerabilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately decommission all acquired systems without assessment</b>: decommissioning without assessment could disrupt legitimate business operations unnecessarily.</span><span class='qd'><b>Grant unrestricted network access to all acquired systems</b>: unrestricted access before assessment could introduce significant risk to the existing environment.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-099","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"med","q":"A security manager is evaluating whether to accept, mitigate, transfer, or avoid a risk related to a legacy system that cannot be easily replaced. Choosing to purchase cyber insurance to offset potential financial loss is an example of:","options":["Risk avoidance","Risk transfer","Risk acceptance","Risk mitigation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Risk transfer</strong> — purchasing insurance shifts the financial impact of a potential loss to a third party, which is the defining characteristic of risk transfer.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk avoidance</b>: would involve eliminating the activity or system entirely, not offsetting financial impact.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk acceptance</b>: means knowingly retaining the risk without further action, which is not what purchasing insurance does.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk mitigation</b>: involves implementing controls to reduce likelihood or impact directly, not shifting financial consequences to a third party.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-100","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"hard","q":"A security manager finds that a compensating control implemented six months ago to address an unpatched vulnerability has never been retested. What is the MOST significant risk of this oversight?","options":["The organization may pay slightly more in software licensing fees","The compensating control's continued effectiveness is unverified, potentially leaving the original vulnerability exploitable without detection","The vulnerability will automatically patch itself over time","Employee morale will decline due to lack of testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The compensating control's continued effectiveness is unverified, potentially leaving the original vulnerability exploitable without detection</strong> — compensating controls must be periodically retested to confirm they still adequately mitigate the risk, especially as environments and threats change; without retesting, a false sense of security may mask real exposure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization may pay slightly more in software licensing fees</b>: licensing cost is unrelated to the risk of an unverified compensating control.</span><span class='qd'><b>The vulnerability will automatically patch itself over time</b>: vulnerabilities do not self-remediate; failing to retest does not cause or prevent this.</span><span class='qd'><b>Employee morale will decline due to lack of testing</b>: morale is not the primary risk concern in this control-assurance scenario.</span>"}
]);
